  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article titled \"SENSE EPI reconstruction with 2D phase error correction and channel\u2010wise noise removal,\" published in 2022 in the journal Magnetic Resonance in Medicine, has garnered notable academic attention with 10 citations and has achieved proven downstream reuse. Funded by Rosetrees, this research reflects significant institutional engagement from key organizations, including Great Ormond Street Hospital and Queen Mary University of London, and is relevant in multiple countries, particularly the United Kingdom and the United States.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work by Elizabeth Powell, Torben Schneider, Marco Battiston, Francesco Grussu, and Ahmed Toosy, among others, focuses on advancing the field of magnetic resonance imaging through innovative methods like 2D phase error correction. This study has made a meaningful impact within the academic community, as evidenced by the 10 citations it has received across various platforms, including articles in the same journal and bioRxiv, illustrating its relevance and integration into current research discussions.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the research highlights the importance of collaboration across esteemed institutions such as Great Ormond Street Hospital and Queen Mary University of London, alongside contributions from industry stakeholders like Philips in Finland. This institutional backing not only lends credibility to the findings but also showcases the geographic scope of the research's influence, with significant citing activity from both the United Kingdom and the United States.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Importantly, this paper reflects a commitment to scientific stewardship through its proven downstream reuse. The methodologies and concepts presented in the study are being actively applied in subsequent research, ensuring that the contributions of this work extend beyond its initial publication. Such downstream effects indicate a robust integration of the research into ongoing studies and innovations within the field of magnetic resonance imaging.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In summary, the combination of academic citations, institutional recognition, and proven downstream reuse demonstrates a strong impact of this article. The financial support from Rosetrees further validates the ongoing relevance of this research area, hinting at future developments that could advance imaging technologies for clinical applications.</p>",
